In [18]:
#Removing outliers
#identify the IQR and upper and lower bound of global sales data 

#Getting list of global sales and sorting them
globalSales = top3000since2006['globalSales'].tolist()
globalSales.sort()
#Computting IQR, Q1, and Q3
Q1 = np.median(globalSales[:len(globalSales) // 2])
Q3 = np.median(globalSales[len(globalSales) // 2:])
IQR = Q3 - Q1
print("This is IQR:", IQR)

#computing lower and upper bounds
lowerBound = Q1 - (IQR * 1.5)
upperBound = Q3 + (IQR * 1.5)
print("This is lower bound:", lowerBound)
print("This is upper bound:", upperBound)

This is IQR: 0.8899999999999999
This is lower bound: -0.845
This is upper bound: 2.715

In [35]:
#In the following blocks, we will be making bins for our global sales
#Originally we had planned to make 3 bins:
#low, mid, and high performing games
#However, as we continued with the project, we realized this is not a good idea, because the midperforming bin
#was unnecessary. Realistically, consumers and producers of video games do not classify their products as "midperforming"
#Usually it either is  a success or a failure. Furthermore, the boundaries of what is considered "midperforming" would technically
#Vary per publisher, so any boudaries we would have made would just reflect our own biases.As a result our accuracy rate would also 
#be dramatically lower.
In [36]:
# create bin limits for classification of global sales column
#An example of when we used 3 bins
'''
#Compute bin size as (max-min) / 3
globalSalesRange = top3000since2006_standardized['globalSales'].max() - top3000since2006_standardized['globalSales'].min()
binSize = globalSalesRange // 3
print("Bin size:", binSize)

#compute the boundaries of the 3 bins
lowBin = [top3000since2006_standardized['globalSales'].min(), top3000since2006_standardized['globalSales'].min() + binSize]
midBin = [lowBin[1] + 1, lowBin[1] + 1 + binSize]
highBin = [midBin[1] + 1, top3000since2006_standardized['globalSales'].max()]
print('Low Bin Boundary:', lowBin)
print('Mid Bin Boundary:', midBin)
print('High Bin Boundary:', highBin)

#In the next few cells, we need to use one-hot encoding to convert our qualitative variables into quantitative ones
#In order to acheive this we made each classification its own feature with 1 meaning it has this feature
#and 0 meaning it doesn't have this feature.
#This was necessary in order to create our model.

#We needed to complete this for the categories of platform and genre. 
#For Platform, we grouped them into companies. For example, we combined GameCube, DS systems, and Wii systems
#All under the company of Nintendo
#Therefore our new column "Company" now has 4 possible values: "Nintendo", "Sony", "Microsoft", "PC"
#Then after making this column we used 1 hot encoding to make 4 different columns of binary values to determine 
#which company the game is from

#For Genre, we just used 1 hot encoding to encompass all the different genre for games. That ended up being a total of 12 more features.

#We used entropy as our formula
